```javascript
// Node class
class Node {
    constructor(value) {
        this.value = value;
        this.next = null;
    }
}

// LinkedList class
class LinkedList {
    constructor() {
        this.head = null;
    }

    // Method to add a new node to the end of the list
    append(value) {
        let newNode = new Node(value);
        if (this.head === null) {
            this.head = newNode;
        } else {
            let current = this.head;
            while (current.next !== null) {
                current = current.next;
            }
            current.next = newNode;
        }
    }

    // Method to print the list
    print() {
        let current = this.head;
        let result = '';
        while (current !== null) {
            result += current.value + ' -> ';
            current = current.next;
        }
        result += 'null';
        console.log(result);
    }
}

// Example usage:
let myList = new LinkedList();
myList.append(1);
myList.append(2);
myList.append(3);
myList.print(); // Outputs: 1 -> 2 -> 3 -> null
```

In this example, we have created two classes: `Node`, which represents each individual element in the linked list, and `LinkedList`, which manages the overall list. The `append` method adds a new node to the end of the list, and the `print` method displays the contents of the list.

The linked list is a versatile data structure that can be used to implement other data structures such as stacks and queues, and it's particularly useful when you need to efficiently insert and remove elements from the beginning or end of a sequence.

